SIMPLE: lucern
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lucern
<hw>Lu"cern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymology
uncertain.]</ety> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sort of hunting dog; -- perhaps from
<xex>Lucerne</xex>, in Switzerland.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My <qex>lucerns</qex>, too, or dogs inured to hunt⟦br⟧
Beasts of most rapine.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An animal whose fur was formerly much in request (by
some supposed to be the lynx).</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>lusern</asp> and <asp>luzern</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The polecat, mastern, and the richskinned <qex>lucern</qex>⟦br⟧
I know to chase.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lucern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lucern
<hw>Lu"cern</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>luzerne</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A leguminous plant (<spn>Medicago sativa</spn>),
having bluish purple cloverlike flowers, cultivated for fodder; --
called also <altname>alfalfa</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>lucerne</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lucern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lucern
<hw>Lu"cern</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>lucerna</ets>.]</ety>
<def>A lamp.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Lydgate.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lucernal</ent>⟦br⟧
